We all die someday.  Physicians know the value of a peaceful death, both for the dying and for those who survive them.  It is the greatest final gift we can give.

Many providers I've met in later abortion care have similar passions for hospice care. We take care of people facing beginning- and end-of-life care at the same time, for the child they would so love to welcome into the world under different circumstances.

I texted with the sister, "hey, maybe try this." And she did.  And the next time she suggested a hospice, the patient was just fine with it.

I got a text a few weeks later about her "getting her angel wings," at peace with herself and her sister.

I may not have discussed all of my religious views with her, but I never lied to her. And we became close enough for me to ask, "what would you like your sister to do?" and her to suggest, "maybe just sit there and read me some Bible verses."

After a week of failed dispos, I adopted a policy. After sign out every day, I went and sat with her for half an hour. I pulled out all of my Biblical literacy and we traded verses and talked about her sister's interpretation of a loving God.

She was a full human in every way, but in a narrow medical view she was a dispo nightmare. One hospice was in a neighborhood she'd had a bad experience in decades earlier. A hospice that her sister found and liked? Well then she couldn't trust it.

Her sister was AMAZING and had tracked her down and pulled her out of neglectful care elsewhere. But the patient didn't trust her sister, because the sister had subtly different religious views (loving God vs. brimstone), and their visits were all tense and confrontational.
